Blood vessels were obscure in most specimens, but where visible, they appeared variable. There was only one obvious lateral pair in some segments, but other segments clearly had two. In addition, branching of these vessels appeared to be minimal compared with most R. (
Sutroa
) species (Appendix 3 ). Specimens from Orogrande Creek had smaller spermathecae and penial structures, and much weaker atrial musculature (
Fig. 8
G–H), but the basic form of these structures resembled those from the type locality, and differed from other species known from the region (
Fend & Brinkhurst 2000
). The single specimen from Hurst Creek, Washington represents a considerable range extension, and the everted condition of its penial bulbs makes comparison with the Idaho material difficult. Nevertheless, the entire structure conforms to the expected everted state of the Idaho material, and differs from other R. (
Sutroa
) species.
